# LaTeX fraction with joules over grams, such as \frac{14J}{23g} or \frac{14 J}{23 g}
\\frac\{(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*J\}\{(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*g\}	\1 jools divided by \2 grams	0	1
# LaTeX fraction with kilojoules over grams, phonetic reading
\\frac\{(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*kJ\}\{(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*g\}	\1 killuh jools divided by \2 grams	0	1
# generic LaTeX fraction fallback; works only when NVDA receives literal LaTeX text
\\frac\{([^{}]+)\}\{([^{}]+)\}	\1 divided by \2	0	1
# full effective heat capacity equation with unicode subscripts
Effective heat capacity \(J/°C\)\s?=\s?\(Mass of H₂O\s?[×x*✕]\s?cH₂O\)\s?\+\s?\(mass of excess H₂\s?[×x*✕]\s?cH₂\)	Effective heat capacity in jools per degree Celsius equals mass of H two O times c of H two O plus mass of excess H two times c of H two	0	1
# full effective heat capacity equation with plain-number formulas
Effective heat capacity \(J/°C\)\s?=\s?\(Mass of H2O\s?[×x*✕]\s?cH2O\)\s?\+\s?\(mass of excess H2\s?[×x*✕]\s?cH2\)	Effective heat capacity in jools per degree Celsius equals mass of H two O times c of H two O plus mass of excess H two times c of H two	0	1
# Google Docs equation paste: numerator/denominator glued on copy (e.g. 29 dogs30 rats)
(\d+\s+[^\d\n]+?)(?<=[a-zA-Z])(\d+\s+[^\d\n]+)	\1 divided by \2	0	1
# Division symbol
÷	divided by	0	0
